<section class="card">
  <h2>About Cauliflower</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    A precision cool-season crop—timing and steady growth determine success.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Cauliflower is sensitive to both heat stress and growth interruptions.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), cauliflower viability depends on fitting head formation inside a stable cool window with enough accumulated seasonal heat to reach maturity before first frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Unlike more forgiving brassicas, cauliflower reacts strongly to stress. Uneven temperatures, stalled growth, or heat spikes can disrupt head formation. In short seasons, margin for error is smaller than with cabbage or broccoli.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors:</strong> 6–8 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Transplant:</strong> near last frost into cool, stable conditions</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 60–100 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light (protect from hard freezes)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are planning baselines. Cauliflower is less forgiving than many crops when timing drifts.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature Sensitivity & Growth Stability</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 60–70°F (16–21°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress risk:</strong> Above ~80°F (27°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Cold slowdown:</strong> Below ~45°F (7°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Cauliflower tolerates light frost, but repeated freezing can reduce head quality.
    More commonly, heat spikes or growth stalls disrupt curd formation before frost becomes the limiting factor.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Indoor Starts Are Recommended</h2>

  <p>
    In short seasons, cauliflower is typically started indoors so transplants enter the garden at a controlled stage.
    This allows you to:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Protect early growth from cold soil stalls</li>
    <li>Align head formation with cool-season weeks</li>
    <li>Preserve risk margin before first frost</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a> to calculate indoor start timing from your frost dates.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~900–1,300 GDD (base 50) depending on variety</p>

  <p>
    Although cauliflower prefers cool conditions, it still requires accumulated seasonal heat to build plant mass before heading.
    Weak heat accumulation can delay maturity and reduce buffer before frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For a full explanation of frost boundaries and seasonal heat budgets working together, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Many cauliflower varieties require <strong>60–100 frost-free days</strong> to reach harvest, depending on type and growing stability.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because cauliflower is stress-sensitive, short frost windows leave less tolerance for planting delays or cool-season slowdowns.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Sometimes (early varieties + precise timing required)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless heat accumulation is strong and transplant timing is exact</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful for stabilizing early growth (light cover), not for pushing through hard freezes</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Cauliflower tolerates light frost, but sustained freezing can damage curds and outer leaves.
    For frost-first modeling, treat 32°F (0°C) as the seasonal boundary and aim to mature heads with buffer ahead of repeated freezing events.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Select early or short-season varieties when frost window is tight</li>
    <li>Start indoors to protect early-stage growth</li>
    <li>Maintain steady moisture and avoid growth stalls</li>
    <li>Use full sun exposure to preserve effective heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, cauliflower viability depends on matching maturity length to your frost-free window and maintaining enough seasonal heat for stable development.
    When buffer is thin, timing slips and temperature swings become the primary failure mode.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can cauliflower survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    It tolerates light frost, but repeated or hard freezes can reduce head quality. For planning, use 32°F (0°C) as the boundary.
  </p>

  <h3>Why didn’t my cauliflower form a proper head?</h3>
  <p>
    Stress from temperature swings, stalled growth, or heat spikes often disrupts curd formation before frost is even a factor.
  </p>

  <h3>Is cauliflower harder than cabbage?</h3>
  <p>
    Generally yes. Cauliflower has less tolerance for growth interruptions and requires tighter alignment between frost window and development speed.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) frost timing as the boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Typical maturity: 60–100 days, ~900–1,300 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Less forgiving than many brassicas—timing precision matters.</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>